│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash occurs due to an assertion failure in     │
│ SmallVector::operator[] accessing Scalars[Mask[I]] with an index that is out  │
│ of bounds. This happens inside reorderScalars when processing a reordering    │
│ mask. The mask can contain special placeholders that are not valid indices    │
│ into Scalars, which reorderScalars does not currently filter out.\n\n2.       │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log shows the SLP vectorizer performing       │
│ reordering propagation (reorderBottomToTop), computing orders and masks via   │
│ inversePermutation(Order, Mask), and fixupOrderingIndices(Order). Notably,    │
│ for stores, the code constructs a \"CurrentOrder\" using E (order size) as a  │
│ sentinel for gaps, then fixupOrderingIndices on it. Later, for split          │
│ vectorize nodes, it computes Mask and MaskOrder and calls reorderSplitNode,   │
│ and for operands that are gathers, it directly calls                          │
│ reorderScalars(OpTE.Scalars, Mask).\nThe first actual transformation is       │
│ reorderScalars, and the crash stack confirms we abort at                      │
│ SmallVector::operator[] when using Mask[I] as an index into Scalars.\n\n3.    │
│ Root Cause Analysis:\nreorderScalars assumes that Mask entries are either     │
│ valid indices in [0, Scalars.size()) or PoisonMaskElem (-1). However,         │
│ upstream code (e.g., when handling stores) builds orders and masks where some │
│ entries represent gaps using E (the vector width), which is not               │
│ PoisonMaskElem. After inversePermutation and fixupOrderingIndices, masks can  │
│ contain entries equal to E or otherwise out-of-range. reorderScalars only     │
│ skips PoisonMaskElem but does not skip indices >= Scalars.size(). As a        │
│ result, it tries to write Scalars[E], triggering the assertion idx < size().  │
│ This is consistent with the log showing building CurrentOrder(E, E) followed  │
│ by transformations.\nTherefore, the bug is that reorderScalars does not guard │
│ against out-of-range mask indices that are used as sentinels elsewhere in     │
│ SLP.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nEdit file                                 │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, lines 1274-1281, to make     │
│ reorderScalars robust to out-of-range mask indices by skipping any mask entry │
│ that is PoisonMaskElem or not within [0, Scalars.size()).\n\nProposed         │
│ change:\n- Current code:\n  for (unsigned I = 0, E = Prev.size(); I < E;      │
│ ++I)\n    if (Mask[I] != PoisonMaskElem)\n      Scalars[Mask[I]] =            │
│ Prev[I];\n\n- Updated code:\n  for (unsigned I = 0, E = Prev.size(); I < E;   │
│ ++I) {\n    int M = Mask[I];\n    if (M == PoisonMaskElem)\n      continue;\n │
│ if (M < 0 || static_cast<unsigned>(M) >= Scalars.size())\n      continue; //  │
│ Sentinel or invalid index, skip.\n    Scalars[static_cast<unsigned>(M)] =     │
│ Prev[I];\n  }\n\nThis preserves existing behavior for valid indices while     │
│ safely ignoring sentinels such as E or any invalid entries introduced by mask │
│ construction. It also keeps assertion semantics elsewhere intact.\n\n5.       │
│ Conclusion:\nThe crash is caused by reorderScalars using mask entries that    │
│ can be out-of-range sentinels, leading to invalid indexing into Scalars. By   │
│ updating reorderScalars to skip any mask element that is PoisonMaskElem or    │
│ not a valid index, we prevent the assertion failure and correctly handle      │
│ masks produced by inversePermutation/fixupOrderingIndices and other           │
│ reordering logic. This fix aligns reorderScalars with the mask semantics used │
│ throughout SLP, eliminating the abort for the given reproducer and similar    │
│ cases."})                                                                     │
