│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash occurs due to an assertion failure in SmallVector::operator[]       │
│ accessing Scalars[Mask[I]] with an index that is out of bounds. This happens  │
│ inside reorderScalars when processing a reordering mask. The mask can contain │
│ special placeholders that are not valid indices into Scalars, which           │
│ reorderScalars does not currently filter out.                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug log shows the SLP vectorizer performing reordering propagation      │
│ (reorderBottomToTop), computing orders and masks via                          │
│ inversePermutation(Order, Mask), and fixupOrderingIndices(Order). Notably,    │
│ for stores, the code constructs a "CurrentOrder" using E (order size) as a    │
│ sentinel for gaps, then fixupOrderingIndices on it. Later, for split          │
│ vectorize nodes, it computes Mask and MaskOrder and calls reorderSplitNode,   │
│ and for operands that are gathers, it directly calls                          │
│ reorderScalars(OpTE.Scalars, Mask).                                           │
│ The first actual transformation is reorderScalars, and the crash stack        │
│ confirms we abort at SmallVector::operator[] when using Mask[I] as an index   │
│ into Scalars.                                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ reorderScalars assumes that Mask entries are either valid indices in [0,      │
│ Scalars.size()) or PoisonMaskElem (-1). However, upstream code (e.g., when    │
│ handling stores) builds orders and masks where some entries represent gaps    │
│ using E (the vector width), which is not PoisonMaskElem. After                │
│ inversePermutation and fixupOrderingIndices, masks can contain entries equal  │
│ to E or otherwise out-of-range. reorderScalars only skips PoisonMaskElem but  │
│ does not skip indices >= Scalars.size(). As a result, it tries to write       │
│ Scalars[E], triggering the assertion idx < size(). This is consistent with    │
│ the log showing building CurrentOrder(E, E) followed by transformations.      │
│ Therefore, the bug is that reorderScalars does not guard against out-of-range │
│ mask indices that are used as sentinels elsewhere in SLP.                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit file llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp, lines 1274-1281,   │
│ to make reorderScalars robust to out-of-range mask indices by skipping any    │
│ mask entry that is PoisonMaskElem or not within [0, Scalars.size()).          │
│                                                                               │
│ Proposed change:                                                              │
│ - Current code:                                                               │
│   for (unsigned I = 0, E = Prev.size(); I < E; ++I)                           │
│     if (Mask[I] != PoisonMaskElem)                                            │
│       Scalars[Mask[I]] = Prev[I];                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ - Updated code:                                                               │
│   for (unsigned I = 0, E = Prev.size(); I < E; ++I) {                         │
│     int M = Mask[I];                                                          │
│     if (M == PoisonMaskElem)                                                  │
│       continue;                                                               │
│     if (M < 0 || static_cast<unsigned>(M) >= Scalars.size())                  │
│       continue; // Sentinel or invalid index, skip.                           │
│     Scalars[static_cast<unsigned>(M)] = Prev[I];                              │
│   }                                                                           │
│                                                                               │
│ This preserves existing behavior for valid indices while safely ignoring      │
│ sentinels such as E or any invalid entries introduced by mask construction.   │
│ It also keeps assertion semantics elsewhere intact.                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is caused by reorderScalars using mask entries that can be          │
│ out-of-range sentinels, leading to invalid indexing into Scalars. By updating │
│ reorderScalars to skip any mask element that is PoisonMaskElem or not a valid │
│ index, we prevent the assertion failure and correctly handle masks produced   │
│ by inversePermutation/fixupOrderingIndices and other reordering logic. This   │
│ fix aligns reorderScalars with the mask semantics used throughout SLP,        │
│ eliminating the abort for the given reproducer and similar cases.             │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
